(thirdQuint)Device-detected Paroxysmal Atrial Fibrillation.

 The modified Microlife blood pressure monitor is able to detect atrial fibrillation (AF) with high sensitivity (95%) and specificity (86%) and has a positive predictive value of 68% and negative predictive value of 98% for single readings.

 In addition, the modified device was also able to accurately classify the majority of the anomalous non-AF rhythms, although the specificity was highly variable, dependent upon the rhythm.

 However sinus rhythm was detected with a specificity of 97%.

 However, we do not currently know if the device would demonstrate a similar sensitivity in detecting AF in patients with paroxysmal AF.

 Therefore, the present study will assess the sensitivity and specificity of the automated oscillometric device using a new AF algorithm among pacemaker patients with fast AF and atrial high-rate episodes and evaluate the effect of the specific rhythm abnormalities on the specificity for AF.

